<title>
Bat use of abandoned mines on BLM lands in
southwestern Montana 1997-1998
</title>
</citeinfo>
</citation>
<descript>
<abstract>
This data set provides information on the use by
bats of abandoned mine workings (77 adits, 96
"shafts" and pits) at 88 mine sites in
southwestern Montana that were investigated in
1997-98.  Locations are recorded in tabular form
in a final report.  Many of the sites were
recorded on a differentially correctable Trimble
Geoexplorer II GPS unit, but not all sites have
GPS determined locations.  All sites were recorded
to quarter-quarter Section precision as described
in tables in the final report.  Data are not in a
GIS.  Bat use was determined by trapping or
netting at mine entrances, or remotely recording
echolocation activity with ultrasonic sensors.
Presence of guano was also used to ascertain use
by bats.  Evidence of bat use was obtained at 66
workings of 49 mine sites, as documented in the
final report.  Four species of bats were confirmed
using workings, based on captures of 64
individuals.  All data in this report have been
provided to resource managers at the Bureau of
Land Management, Dillon Resource Area, Dillon, MT.
</abstract>
<purpose>
Abandoned mine openings will be closed by the
Bureau of Land Management for safety.  Locations
with evidence of use by bats may be gated rather
than closed.  This data set documents evidence of
use by bats at some of these sites to assist in
decisions to close or gate mine openings.
</purpose>
</descript>
